  "body": "Your guide to the WSJ’s exclusive reporting and analysis.               Is this email difficult to read? View in browser   https://10point.cmail19.com/t/d-e-gkkuhid-dknirndy-z/                                                                                                   \r\n\r\nSponsored By\r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n✏️ United Airlines’ card-counting CEO made a huge bet on brand loyalty. It’s paying off. Scott Kirby made a risky wager that premium features would convince travelers to pay more for United flights. The Journal’s Alison Sider and Ben Cohen report on the executive’s  high-stakes push to transform air travel [https://www.wsj.com/business/airlines/united-airlines-ceo-scott-kirby-delta-american-11621d97] from a commodity into an experience.\r\n\r\nEmma Tucker\r\n\r\nEditor in Chief, The Wall Street Journal\r\n\r\nTODAY'S HEADLINES\r\n\r\n1\r\n\r\nTensions between Iranian leaders over talks with the U.S.  spilled into the open [https://www.wsj.com/world/middle-east/irans-leadership-divisions-frustrate-efforts-to-make-progress-in-talks-f87fac3a] this week, highlighting how difficult it will be for President Trump to secure the diplomatic win he wants to end the war.  Follow live coverage [https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/iran-war-us-trump-2026], with officials from Iran and the U.S. set to be in Pakistan in the coming days.  United Airlines  went all-in on premium features [https://www.wsj.com/business/airlines/united-airlines-ceo-scott-kirby-delta-american-11621d97] and brand loyalty, and the strategy is lifting the airline into Delta’s airspace.  Democrats are  successfully countering Trump’s redistricting push [https://www.wsj.com/politics/elections/obama-democrats-congressional-map-redistricting-97e39b4c] by fighting fire with fire, buoyed by former President Barack Obama’s decision to back gerrymandering efforts he once opposed.   The Trump administration has  lobbied against legislation that would regulate AI [https://www.wsj.com/politics/policy/trump-republican-state-ai-regulation-74fd83c6] in at least six GOP-led states, deepening a division within the party over the White House’s industry-friendly AI agenda.  GLP-1 drugs are  complicating the wedding-gown business [https://www.wsj.com/style/fashion/glp-1-weight-loss-medication-wedding-dress-waiver-15f51978], prompting bridal stores to stock more dresses to accommodate last-minute weight fluctuations.\r\n\r\nFROM THE MARKETS\r\n\r\n2\r\n\r\nThe arrest of a U.S. soldier charged with using classified information to place lucrative bets on Polymarket is a  watershed moment for prediction markets [https://www.wsj.com/finance/currencies/arrest-of-u-s-soldier-signals-polymarkets-wild-west-days-are-ending-5d31ea69], heralding a new era of stricter government enforcement.  Most Americans think the job market will get worse.  Here’s why that matters [https://www.wsj.com/economy/most-americans-think-the-job-market-will-get-worse-heres-why-that-matters-d121585a].\r\n\r\nREAD IT HERE FIRST\r\n\r\n3\r\n\r\nU.S. energy exports are hitting records as the world adjusts to a closed Persian Gulf.\r\n\r\nThe war in the Middle East has bolstered America’s status as an energy-exporting powerhouse, with  Asia and Europe clamoring for shipments [https://www.wsj.com/business/energy-oil/us-energy-exports-persian-gulf-closure-588c257e] of U.S. crude, natural gas and jet fuel. U.S. exports of crude and petroleum products rose to a record last week, nearly 12.9 million barrels a day, according to the U.S. Energy Information Administration. For now, countries have few other choices, and the frenzy shows no signs of slowing. Yet the U.S. will face obstacles turning wartime demand into a longer-term boost, report Chelsey Dulaney and Jason Douglas.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n4\r\n\r\nTucker Carlson told WSJ why he is turning on Trump.\r\n\r\nThe former Fox News host and onetime Trump confidant is now the most prominent opponent of the Iran war—and a potential problem for a president who demands total loyalty, reports Philip Wegmann. In an  interview with the Journal [https://www.wsj.com/politics/tucker-carlson-trump-relationship-05781c57], Carlson said the war shows Trump has been captured by neoconservatives: “I don’t hate Trump. I hate this war and the direction that the U.S. government is taking. I feel betrayed.” Carlson described the man he helped make president a second time as charming, intelligent and an existential threat to self-government.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMake sense of AI’s impact on business.\r\n\r\nSign up for  WSJ AI & Business [https://www.wsj.com/newsletters/wsj-ai-business], a free weekly newsletter packed with news, insights and data from our global team of technology journalists.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n              CONTENT FROM: FOX ONE          MLB on FOX and More on FOX One   [http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/clk?id=7145480861&iu=/2]\r\n\r\nThe 2026 MLB season is in full swing and streaming live all season long on FOX One. Catch over 85 regular season games—including 23 Saturday matchups—plus the All-Star Game and the World Series on the FOX One app, the streaming home for everything FOX. Stream FOX Sports, FOX News, FOX Business and FOX Weather alongside hit entertainment shows live or on-demand, all in one place.\r\n\r\nLearn More [http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/clk?id=7145480861&iu=/2]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nEXPERT TAKE\r\n\r\n5\r\n\r\nQ: What’s it like to retire in America after a divorce?\r\n\r\nWhile national divorce rates have hit historic lows for younger generations, the rate for older Americans has climbed. Several people spoke to reporters Veronica Dagher and Anne Tergesen about their  post-divorce retirement lives [https://www.wsj.com/personal-finance/divorce-retirement-america-6d03e3e2].\r\n\r\nA: For many Americans, their golden years are being rewritten by divorce.\r\n\r\nThese late-stage splits often upend retirement plans, forcing people to navigate expenses with halved 401(k)s and little time to shore up their savings. That’s all while facing the daunting task of rebuilding their lives. Yet many end up finding a sense of freedom in their newfound independence. We spoke with four retirees about how they successfully navigated life after divorce:\r\n\r\nMark Sutton, 74, spends $240,000 annually. He told us that his divorce in 2014 slashed his net worth. He and his former wife divided his pension and his $1.1 million 401(k). He also paid her for her share of the value of their home, which he still lives in. To make up for the financial setback, Sutton postponed his retirement from age 65 to 70.  Lynn Meinor, 70, spends $86,000 annually. She told us that when she realized she might be heading for a divorce three decades ago, she made a key decision with her retirement in mind. Instead of taking a job in the private sector, she joined the Utah Department of Health & Human Services. A big draw was the state’s pension.\r\n\r\nRead WSJ’s  full series on the cost of divorce [https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-cost-of-divorce-ed8ac3ef?mod=article_inline&_gl=1*1b0z61p*_gcl_au*MTg2NTEwMjcxNS4xNzc3MDQ4MjY2*_ga*MTcyNTA2MTY3MC4xNzExNTU0NTI0*_ga_K2H7B9JRSS*czE3NzcwNDgyNjMkbzEkZzEkdDE3NzcwNDgzOTMkajYwJGwwJGgxNzg4NzE3NzY3].\r\n\r\nSEE THE STORY\r\n\r\n6\r\n\r\nIs the world ready for a car without a rear window?            \r\n\r\nPHOTO: POLESTAR\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Polestar 4 forgoes a conventional rearview mirror—or a rear window, period—and instead uses a video display and a rear-facing camera. The Journal’s Dan Neil asks:  Are consumers ready for this [https://www.wsj.com/lifestyle/cars/polestar-4-dan-neil-review-407f11a6]?\r\n\r\nHAPPENING THIS WEEKEND\r\n\r\n7\r\n\r\nSaturday: The White House Correspondents’ Dinner, which Trump will attend for the first time as president.  Sunday: The Michael Jackson biopic “Michael,” which is  poised to be a hit despite prior controversy [https://www.wsj.com/business/media/the-michael-jackson-biopic-that-nearly-blew-up-is-poised-to-be-a-hit-12315f64], will wrap up its opening weekend.  📰  Today's paper [http://ereader.wsj.net/?]\r\n\r\nTHE NUMBER\r\n\r\n8\r\n\r\n          11,900          \r\n\r\nHow many words the average American spoke every day in 2019, down from 16,632 in 2005, according to researchers at the University of Missouri-Kansas City and the University of Arizona. All told,  our speaking decreased [https://www.wsj.com/health/wellness/speaking-study-words-per-day-decline-6f549d5a] about 28% in that time period. Loneliness could become an even greater problem as we retreat into online spaces, and speaking less could lead to a decline in the cognitive chess game of conversation, writes Julie Jargon.\r\n\r\nAND FINALLY...\r\n\r\n9\r\n\r\nWhy Tulsa, an unlikely cultural capital, should be on your travel list.\r\n\r\nOnce an oil boomtown, the Oklahoma city is experiencing another kind of resurgence. This time, a new wave of transplants is being  drawn in by Tulsa's affordability [https://www.wsj.com/lifestyle/travel/why-tulsa-an-unlikely-cultural-capital-should-be-on-your-travel-list-191544d7], slower pace and open spaces. They are collaborating with longtime locals to turn the central neighborhoods of the sprawling city into an unlikely hub for art, culture and gastronomy.\r\n\r\nBEYOND THE NEWSROOM\r\n\r\n10\r\n\r\nOpinion: The progressive campaign to  discredit the current Supreme Court [https://www.wsj.com/opinion/supreme-court-leaked-memos-obama-clean-power-plan-john-roberts-3d27ce3d] escalated with the publication of confidential memos. The real scandal is the methods the political left is using to subvert the Court.\r\n\r\nWSJ | Buy Side: The  best cheap car insurance providers [https://www.wsj.com/buyside/personal-finance/auto-insurance/cheapest-car-insurance] offer low rates but don’t skimp on coverage options.\r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\nAbout Us\r\n\r\nThe 10-Point is your guide to The Wall Street Journal's reporting and analysis you can't get anywhere else. Your subscription makes our journalism possible.\r\n\r\nToday's newsletter was curated and edited by Conor Grant and Michael Wright in collaboration with Editor in Chief Emma Tucker. Got a tip for us? Here's  how to submit [https://www.wsj.com/tips].\r\n\r\n Unsubscribe [http://www.wsj.com/newsletters?unsub=197&addr=d4ae6d32bd4db70c10900a8884d402000bb7d1fd78e887a1ed41df81457d62ff3e]      Unsubscribe https://10point.cmail19.com/t/d-u-gkkuhid-dknirndy-v/            Newsletters & Alerts [https://www.wsj.com/newsletters]            Contact Us [https://customercenter.wsj.com/public?url=https://customercenter.wsj.com/view/contactus.html]            Privacy Notice [https://dowjones.com/privacy-notice]            Cookie Notice [https://dowjones.com/cookie-notice]                             Dow Jones & Company, Inc. 4300 U.S. Ro‌ute 1 No‌rth Monm‌outh Junc‌tion, N‌J 088‌52\r\n\r\nYou are currently subscribed as wschenk@gmail.com. For further assistance, please contact Customer Service at support@wsj.com or 1-800-JOURNAL.\r\n\r\nCopyright 2026 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.   |   All Rights Reserved.\r\n",
